Re: In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for Acquisition of ALLETE by 
Canada Pension Plan Investment Board and Global Infrastructure Partners OAH Docket No. 25- 2500- 40339; Docket No s. E-015/PA -24-198; E -015/M -24-
383 
 Dear Judge McKenzie:  
 
Enclosed for filing in the above -referenced  matter  is the Minnesota Department of 
Commerce’s direct testimony and attachments. By copy of this letter, all parties have been served. 
A copy of the testimony also will be delivered to your office.  A declaration of service also is 
enclosed.  
 
Thank you for your attention to this matter.   
 
Sincerely,  
  s/ Richard Dornfeld  
RICHARD DORNFELD  
Assistant Attorney General  
 (651) 757- 1327 (Voice)  
(651) 297- 1235 (Fax)  
richard.dornfeld@ag.state.mn.us  
 Attorney  for Minnesota Department of Commerce  
 
Enclosures  
 
cc: Service List
 
 DECLARATION OF SERVICE  
 
 
Re: In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for Acquisition of ALLETE by Canada Pension Plan Investment Board and Global Infrastructure Partners  
OAH Docket No. 25- 2500- 40339; Docket No s. E-015/PA -24-198; E -015/M -24-
383  
STATE OF MINNESOTA ) 
 ) ss. 
COUNTY OF RAMSEY ) 
   I, ANN KIRLIN, hereby state that on February 4, 2025, I filed by electronic eDockets the 
attached Minnesota Department of Commerce’s direct testimony and attachments , and 
eServed and/or sent by U.S. Mail, as noted, to all parties on the attached service list. 
See attached service list.  
I declare under penalty of perjury that everything I have stated in this document is true and 
correct.  
 
/s/ Ann Kirlin

(a)“Arm’s length” in this context refers to the independent governance structure of CPP
Investments, which ensures that CPP Investments operates without direct influence orcontrol from the Canadian government. The Canada Pension Plan (“CPP”), which is a
mand atory national pension plan created and managed by the government of Canada and

Phone Number: n/a   participating provinces, was funded by the contributions of employees, employers, and self -
employed people in Canada. In 1997, federal and provincial governments in Canada agreed 
to reform the CPP and establish CPP Investments as the global investment mana gement 
organization with a legislative mandate to invest the CPP fund to help ensure the CPP remains sustainable for the long term. CPP Investments is a Crown corporation, but is neither a Crown agent nor an agent of the federal government. The CPPIB Act provides for a governance model that balances CPP Investments’ statutory mandate and public accountability with its arm’s length relationship with the federal and provincial governments. This governance model is premised on CPP Investments’ need to operate free from political interference so that it can more effectively achieve its statutory investment mandate of investing CPP Investments’ portfolio of assets. CPP Investments does not, and may not, make investments for the purpose of implementing, advancing or promoting policies of the 
government of Canada, and CPP Investments may not in any way be directed by the government as to which investments it may make. CPP Investments does not submit its investment strategy, business plan or compensation policies for  government approval.  
(b)As described above, the Canada Pension Plan Investment Board Act (“CPPIB Act”) establishes an arm’s length relationship and ensures the Canadian government cannot influenceinvestment decisions made by CPP Investments. CPP Investments does not, and may not ,
make investments for the purpose of implementing, advancing, or promoting policies of the government of Canada, and CPP Investments may not in any way be directed by thegovernment as to which investments it may make. Parliament cannot amend the CPPIB Ac t
(or the CPP Act) or pass other laws which directly or indirectly alter the CPPIB Act (or the CPP Act) without cabinet approval of at least two -thirds of all provinces in Canada having at least
two-thirds of the population of those provinces. For context,  this process is more onerous
than the amending formula for Canada’s national constitution
(c)Legislators designed the CPPIB Act to insulate CPP Investments’ Board members frompolitical decision -making. Directors are appointed by the Governor in Council (i.e., the
Governor General of Canada acting on the advice of the cabinet of the government ofCanada) on the recommendation of the federal Minister of Finance, who consults withprovincial finance ministers. Once appointed, directors can only be removed for cause, andthey are bound by fiduciary duties to act in the best interests of CPP Investment s. These
safeguards help ensure that the Board remains independent. Neither the federal Cabinetnor the federal Minister of Finance appoints the President and CEO of CPPIB or any of itsother senior officers. They are appointed by the board of directors.

This question is based on assumptions that are fundamentally incorrect.   First, this question takes the cited sentence out of context, as the more complete segment of the Proxy 
Statement speaks for itself in stating that “Following a public announcement that BlackRock, Inc. (“BlackRock”) had entered into an agreement to acquire GIP, GIP’s Founder, Chairman and Chief 
Executive Officer called Ms. Owen to inform her about the BlackRock transaction. In that call, GIP’s Founder, Chairman and Chief Executive Officer indicated that GIP would continue to manage its investments and that GIP’s transaction with BlackRock did not change GIP’s interest in or the dynamics associated with the proposed transaction with the Company. The Company neither conferred with representatives of BlackRock to discuss the proposed acquisition by GIP (and its  partners) of the 
Company nor did it enter into any agreement with BlackRock relating to or in connection with the proposed transaction.”   
Second, this request improperly  suggests that Ms. Owen had sole or primary decision -making power 
regarding the Acquisition. No one individual, was solely responsible for evaluating the potential 
impacts of other proceedings on the Acquisition and making any corresponding decisions.  
Additionally, this request overemphasizes the significance of BlackRock’s acquisition of GIP to this 
Acquisition. See the Supplemental Filing, dated October 8, 2024. Finally, as set forth in the Petition, 
the Partners share ALLETE’s vision and are aligned  with its values.

 Request:  
 
Reference Lapson Dir ect: State whether this statement is true or false, and explain your answer: 
None of the ring -fencing devices that you describe protect Minnesota Power from the risk that the 
acquirers, because of the risks they take on as investors in other businesses, will be unable to supply the equity capital that the utility needs.  
  
Response:  
 The question appears to be based upon a false premise that the purpose of ring -fencing devices is 
to guarantee to the acquired company funding of equity capital. In fact, the purpose of ring -fencing 
protections is to assure separations between the acquired  utility company and its owners. This 
entails assuring that it can retain access to its physical and financial assets, that it does not bear liabilities relating to its parent and its parent’s other affiliates and businesses, and that it can access its own  borrowing arrangements.    
While it is true that none of the ring -fencing mechanisms provides a guarantee of future equity 
funding, that is not the purpose of ring -fencing. The Partners’ have expressed in their testimony 
that their motivation to acquire ALLETE is to invest equity as  needed in Minnesota Power as a 
sound utility business.

 Request:  
Reference Quackenbush Direct at  14:19- 22: You state: “Large IOUs enjoy greater access to capital 
and a more diverse investor base than  small IOUs. Some small companies cannot issue equity in 
large enough size for some  large public equity investors to participate in investing due to internal 
investment  considerations. ”  In the next paragraph , you describe ALLETE  as small.  
(a) If small is a disadvantage, explain how it is that over the last 60 years , plenty of small utilities 
have raised the capital they need.  
(b) Are you saying that now that FERC and the states have allowed most utilities to merge or be  
acquired so as to leave the U.S. with mostly large utilities, the new reality is that the few utilities that remain unacquired are at a disadvantage?  
(c) If so, would disadvantage not exist had FERC and so many states accommodated the business goals of merger proponents?  
 Response:  
 Minnesota Power and the Partners object to this information request because it is argumentative.  
Subject to and without waiving the foregoing objection, please see the following response:   
  
a. The utility industry has a decades -long record of raising capital to invest in infrastructure 
that benefits customers. Many small utilities have succeeded despite  these disadvantages 
and have successfully raised capital on a standalone basis.   However, ci rcumstances 
change over time, and it is forward -looking expectations that are most important.   
Utilities have the ability to plan capital needs on a forward -looking basis.   In today’s 
environment, with increasing load growth, electrification, and aggressive government policy

(a) Given that the acquirers are offering a premium, and given that they will not seek to recover the premium by including it in the rate base, how will the acquirers recover the premium and

publicly traded investor -owned utilities. Generally speaking, those  transactions have not 
included the recovery of acquisition premiums in the rate base of the acquired utility.

Q9.   Do you agree with Mr. Quackenbush that, after the Michigan Public Service 1 
Commission approved the 2014 UPPCO transaction, “UPPCO maintained its financial 2 
health, continued providing safe, reliable, affordable and adequate service to its 3 
customers, and raised necessary capital while maintaining a reasonable capital 4 
structure”?  5 
A9.  Prior to  the 2014 transaction, UPPCO had unusually high rates for residential and 6 
commercial customers . Based on EIA Form 861 data,5 the average residential bill per kWh in 7 
2014 was $0.2247. In 2017, the calendar year with full effect of the UPPCO transaction, that 8 
had increased to $0.2433 with most of the increase being due to expenses associated with the 9 
transaction. Elimination of the high-cost power purchase agreement between UPPCO and a 10 
legacy affiliate  then brought rates back down to the 22-23 cents per kWh range for the 11 
following few years. I would characterize the initial transfer as exacerbating an affordability 12 
problem, which we were able to push back after a few years of regulatory pressure. 13

Direct Testimony  
Will T. Keyes  
 
 
  
 
 
 
  
Before the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission  
 
State of Minnesota  
  
In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for the Acquisition of ALLETE by Canada  
Pension Plan Investment Board and Global Infrastructure Partners  
 
 
OAH Docket No. 25 -2500 -40339 
MPUC Docket No. E015/PA- 24-198  
 
 
 
 
 
IBEW Local 31 Testimony  
 
 
 
 
 
 
February 4, 2025  
 
  
 
 
 
 
  
 
 
 
 
Table of Contents  
I    Introduction and Qualifications  ................................ ................................ .............................  1 
II  Potential Impacts to Local 31 Members  ................................ ................................ ..................  2 
III Conclusion  ................................ ................................ ................................ .............................  4 
 
Testimony of Will Keyes Business Manager/ Financial Secretary , International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers Local 31  
 
1 
 I. Introduction and Qualifications  1 
Q: Please state your name, affiliation and address. 2 
A: My name is Will T. Keyes, and my business address is 2002 London Road, Suite 105, Duluth, 3 
Minnesota 55812.  4 
 5 
Q: By whom are you employed and in what position?  6 
I am employed by the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 31.  My current position 7 
is Business Manager/Financial Secretary.   8 
 9 
Q: Please describe your experience representing employees of Minnesota Power.  10 
I was appointed to serve as a Union Steward while working as an Electrical Lineworker at 11 
Minnesota Power . In 2013, I was appointed and subsequently elected by Local 31’s membership 12 
to serve as an Executive Board member. I n 2015,  I was appointed Assistant Business Manager of 13 
Local 31.  In 2016, I was elected Business Manager/Financial Secretary of Local 31 . 14 
 15 
Q: What is the purpose of your testimony today? 16 
A: The purpose of my testimony, on behalf of IBEW Local 31, is to outline our thoughts on the 17 
impact of the acquisition on our members.  18 
 19 
Q: Please describe Local 31.  20 
A: Local 31 represents 867 members working under 20 separate labor agreements with 1 8 21 
different employers throughout Northeast Minnesota.  Local 31 has 3 collective bargaining 22 
agreements (CBA ’s) with ALLETE. One CBA covers 3 employees working for ALLETE 23 
Renewable Resources, another covers 54 employees working for Superior Water Light & Power, 24 
and the other with Minnesota Power.  25 
 26 
Q: Please describe the bargaining history between Local 31 and Minnesota Power.  27 
A: Local 31 has been the bargaining representative of unionized employees at Minnesota Power 28 
(“the Company”) since 1937 . Since that time  Local 31 has negotiated dozens of  contracts with the 29 
Company . Currently, Local 31 represents approximately 431 members employed by Minnesota 30 
Power,  who are employed in a variety of classiﬁcations , including but not limited to  those involved 31 
Testimony of Will Keyes Business Manager/ Financial Secretary , International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers Local 31  
 
2 
 in power generation, transmission and distribution, and customer service.  Our members  are 1 
crucial to Minnesota Power’s ability to fulﬁ ll its mission to provide safe and reliable service to its 2 
customers.  3 
 4 
II. Potential Impacts to IBEW Local 31 Members  5 
Q: How do you believe the acquisition of ALLETE by Canada Pension Plan Investment Board 6 
(“CPP Investments”) and Global Infrastructure Partners (“GIP”) would impact the Minnesota 7 
Power employees who you represent? 8 
In the short term, I believe impacts of the acquisition will be minimal. As Minnesota Power has 9 
represented in its Petition, ALLETE will “continue to honor its union contracts. This includes terms 10 
of compensation, beneﬁts, and work conditions among other portions of any applicable union 11 
contract. ALLETE will satisfy all notice, information, consultation, bargaining or consent obligations 12 
owed to any labor union, labor organization or employee representative of any union employee in 13 
connection with the transactions contemplated by the Acquisition ” (M P,  Petitio n, p.18 ). However, 14 
our contract expires on April 30th of 2026.  We do not know if, or what changes may be proposed  or 15 
will occur as a result of those negotiations.  16 
 17 
Q: Are current protections included in the acquisition agreement, namely  that it will honor 18 
union contracts , adequate to protect the employees who you represent? 19 
A: No, the Company has made certain assurances to non -union employees as a condition of the 20 
sale such as : “For the two -year period following the Acquisition…will retain extensive protections, 21 
including the same or better employment position in the same location, and wages, incentive, 22 
beneﬁts, and employee protections no less favorable than those available to the employee 23 
immediately prior to the Acquisition ” ( M P,  Petition , p.18) .  The company has not made this same 24 
commitment to union employees represented by Local 31.   25 
 26 
Q: Does the existing labor agreement have language prohibiting the company from reducing 27 
headcount, or changing work locations?  28 
A: No, there is language in the contract describing how those changes would occur and in what 29 
order, but it does  not prohibit the  company  from laying off employees or  changing their work 30 
location.  31 
Testimony of Will Keyes Business Manager/ Financial Secretary , International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers Local 31  
 
3 
 Q: What acquisition concerns have been brought to you from the memb ers you represent at 1 
Minnesota Power?  2 
A: To date, most concerns have been  related to job security, conditions of employment, and the 3 
potential fo r beneﬁt changes.    4 
 5 
Q: Please expand on the concerns related to job  security.  6 
A: As I noted previously , the company has made certain assurances to non -union employees that 7 
have not been made to union employees.   The company may demand other changes to provisions 8 
of the existing CBA associated with terminations, layoffs, or work location  upon expiration of our 9 
current contract (April 30, 2026), a time lesser than the two years from the close of the Acquisition . 10 
 11 
The utility industry is going through major transformations, particularly on the power generation 12 
front.  As renewable energy sources grow while  fossil fuel generation declines, it is unknown what 13 
generation assets will be owned and operated by the company or where they will be located.  There 14 
is no assurance that new facilities will be staffed with employees represented by Local 31, 15 
particularly those facilities that are located outside of Minnesota or operated by an unregulated 16 
subsidiary such as ALLETE Renewable Resources.  The Company purports that a catalyzing factor in 17 
seeking private investment is the need for signiﬁcant new capital to achieve green energy goals 18 
(Cady Testimony, p 7).  Should the acquiring companies invest the desired  inﬂux of capital into the 19 
Company to build or obtain facilities, assets, or infrastructure, this will potentially hasten changes 20 
to the Minnesota Power portfolio and relative staffing needs.  21 
  22 
Employees have also expressed concerns about future transactions that could result in certain 23 
business segments being spun off to other buyers resulting in Minnesota Power no longer being a 24 
vertically integrated utility.   25 
 26 
Q: Please expand on the concerns related to conditions of employment?  27 
As noted previously, our current contract expires on  April 30th, 2026. At this point, we do not know  28 
what positions ALLETE w ill take in negotiating the successor agreement.  We are concerned that the 29 
Company  may demand substantial changes to existing contract language  that could affect daily 30 
work assignments, working rules and work locations.   31 
Testimony of Will Keyes Business Manager/ Financial Secretary , International Brotherhood 
of Electrical Workers Local 31  
 
4 
 Q: Please explain your memberships concerns related to beneﬁt  security?  1 
Certain represented employees are eligible for beneﬁts that include  but are not limited to the 2 
deﬁned beneﬁt pension plan, retiree medical,  long term disability,  life insurance, etc.  Our 3 
members have also expressed concerns about whether these beneﬁt plans will continue to be in 4 
place and properly funded by the new owners.  5 
 6 
Q: Are beneﬁt plans and funding requirements protected by law?  7 
A: To some extent yes, but not in totality. There are no laws that would  prevent the company from 8 
proposing changes to beneﬁt  levels and/or eligibility for future years of se rvice .  Federal law 9 
currently requires certain funding levels of some, but not all the active and post -employment  10 
beneﬁt plans.  11 
 12 
Q: How many employees represented by Local 31 are active participants in the deﬁned beneﬁt 13 
pension plan?  14 
A: Approximately 190, or 44% of r epresented employees hired prior to January 31, 2011 (CBA, p.37)  15 
are eligible for the  deﬁned beneﬁt pension plan.  Employees hired after February 1, 2011, receive a 16 
401k contribution from the company rather than participating in the pension plan . Employees 17 
under the 401k retirement plan are fully vested.   18 
 19 
Q: How many active  employees are eligible for retiree medical beneﬁts? 20 
A: Approximately 190, or 44% of represented employees are eligible to receive retiree medical 21 
beneﬁts upon reaching age 55.  Like  the pension plan, union e mployees hired on or before January 22 
31, 2011 (CBA, p.96) are eligible for retiree medical beneﬁts upon reaching the eligibility 23 
requirements of the plan.  Union employees hired after February 1, 2011 , are not eligible for retiree 24 
medical beneﬁts.   25 
 26 
III. Conclusion  27 
Q: Does this complete your Direct Testimony?  28 
A: Yes.  29

BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. BEFORE THE  
 
MINNESOTA PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSION 
 
 
In the Matter of the Petition of 
Minnesota Power for Acquisition of ALLETE by Canada Pension Plan Investment Board and Global 
Infrastructure Partners   
 ) 
) ) ) ) ) 
)  
 
DOCKET NO. E015/ PA-24-198 
 
 
Direct Testimony of Christopher C. Walters  
  
I.  INTRODUCTION 1 
Q PLEASE STATE YOUR NAME AND BUSINESS ADDRESS.  2 
A Christopher C. Walters.  My business address is 16690 Swingley Ridge Road, Suite  140, 3 
Chesterfield, MO 63017. 4 
 
Q WHAT IS YOUR OCCUPATION?   5 
A I am a consultant in the field of public utility regulation and a Principal with the firm of 6 
Brubaker & A ssociates, Inc. (“BAI”) , energy, economic and regulatory consultants. 7 
 Q PLEASE DESCRIBE YOUR EDUCATIONAL BACKGROUND AND 8 
EXPERIENCE.  9 
A This information is included in Schedule 1  to my testimony.   10 
 Q ON WHOSE BEHALF ARE YOU APPEARING IN THIS PROCEEDING?  11 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 2 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. A I am testifying on behalf of  the Large Power Intervenors  (“LPI”).  LPI  is an  ad hoc  1 
consortium of Minnesota Power’s largest and most energy -intensive companies.  LPI ’s 2 
members will be directly, and significantly, affected by the outcome of  this proceeding.     3 
 
Q WHAT IS THE PURPOSE OF YOUR DIRECT TESTIMONY?  4 
A In my testimony, I address the proposed acquisition (the “Transaction” or 5 
“Acquisition”) of ALLETE (d/b/a Minnesota Power)  (the “Company”, “ALLETE”, or 6 
“MP”) by Canada Pension Plan Investment Board ( “CPP Investments ”) and Global 7 
Infrastructure Partners ( “GIP”) (collectively , the “Partners”).   8 
 
II.  SUMMARY  9 
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE YOUR TESTIMONY . 10 
A My testimony addresses various aspects of the Acquisition, as judged against the issues 11 
raised by the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission (the “Commission”) in its October 12 
7, 2024 Order for Hearing.1  The overarching request by the Commission in the Order 13 
for Hearing was for the parties to engage in and develop a record pertaining to a cost - 14 
benefit analysis.  I present several potentially harmful outcomes overlooked by the 15 
Applicants and respond to certain claims of potential benefits.  After weighing the 16 
potential harms with the potential benefits, as directed by the Commission, I conclude 17 
that the proposed Acquisition is not in the public interest and recommend the 18 
Commission reject it.  19 
 
1 In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for Acquisition of ALLETE by Canada Pension Plan 
Investment Board and Global Infrastructure Partners , MPUC Docket No. E -015/PA -24-198, Order Requiring 
Additional Information and Granting Intervention, and Notice of and Order for Hearing (October 7, 2024)  
(eDocket No. 202410- 210754 -01) (the “Order for Hearing”) . 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 3 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC.  
III.  OVERVIEW OF THE TRANSACTION 1 
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE THE TRANSACTION AS PROPOSED. 2 
A On July 19, 2024, the Company announced that it would be acquired by entities 3 
managed by the Partners.  The transaction is valued at approximately $6.2 billion, which 4 
includes $3.9 billion for ALLETE's shares and the assumption of $2.3 billion in debt.  5 
Shareholder s of ALLETE will receive $67.00 in cash per share as part of this 6 
acquisition.  Upon closure of the transaction, ALLETE will transition from a publicly 7 
traded company to a privately held entity under Alloy Parent LLC.2   8 
 
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE THE PARTNERS.  9 
A CPP Investments is a professional investment management organization that manages 10 
the Canada Pension Plan Fund, a pension fund for over 22 million contributors and 11 
beneficiaries in Canada.  Operating independently of the CPP and governments, it seeks 12 
to maximize long -term returns for Canadians , while mitigating risk.  As of March 31, 13 
2024, it managed approximately $467.1 billion (C$632.3 billion) in assets, with 14 
significant investments across global markets, including roughly $197.7 billion  15 
(C$267.6 billion)  in the United States.  Its diversified portfolio spans public and private 16 
equities, real estate, infrastructure, and fixed income.3 17 
  GIP, or Global Infrastructure Management, LLC, is an infrastructure investor 18 
founded in 2006, specializing in owning and operating assets in energy, transport, digital 19 
 
2 In the Matter of the Petition of Minnesota Power for the Acquisition of ALLETE by Canada Pension 
Plan Investment Board and Global Infrastructure Partners , MPUC Docket No. E015/PA -24-198, Initial Filing – 
Petition for Approval at 9 -12 (July 19, 2024) (eDocket No. 20247 -208768- 01) (“Petition”).  
3 Id. at 5-7. 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 4 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. infrastructure, and water and waste management sectors.  As of March 31, 2024, GIP 1 
managed approximately $115 billion in assets, with its portfolio companies employing 2 
over 116,000 people.  Toward the end of 2024, BlackRock, Inc. announced the 3 
successful completion of its  acquisition of GIP.  The combined infrastructure platform 4 
will be branded Global Infrastructure Partners, a part of BlackRock. 4 5 
 
Q WHY ARE THE PARTNERS INTERESTED IN ACQUIRING MINNESOTA 6 
POWER?   7 
A Based on the testimony provided by ALLETE and the Partners, the Partners are 8 
motivated to invest in ALLETE’s substantial capital expenditure plan  and, ultimately, 9 
realize a significant return on that investment.  As explained in the testimony of GIP 10 
witness Mr. Bram, GIP views ALLETE as a unique opportunity to invest in a growth- 11 
oriented regulated electric utility with high -quality assets across both regulated utilities 12 
and unregulated renewables, aligning with GIP’s investment criteria.5 The primary 13 
driver of the A cquisition is ALLETE’s significant expected growth in rate base as 14 
Minnesota Power invests to comply with Minnesota’s Carbon Free Standard.6 GIP 15 
asserts that t his compliance requires unprecedented capital investment to decarbonize 16 
Minnesota Power’s generation fleet.7  In addition, GIP is intrigued by Minnesota Power 17 
allegedly needing to invest heavily in its transmission and distribution systems to deliver 18 
this decarbonized energy to the region and its customers.8 In light of this, Mr. Bram 19 
 
4 Id. at 7-9. 
5 Ex. ___ at 4 (Jonathan Bram Direct Testimony) (“Bram Direct”). 
6 Bram Direct  at 4. 
7 Bram Direct  at 4. 
8 Bram Direct  at 4; see also CUB IR 166 and LPI IRs 103 -104, attached hereto as LPI Exhibit ___(CCW), 
Direct Schedule 2.  
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 5 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. asserts that the “scale of these investments and the speed at which they must be deployed 1 
make ALLETE an attractive investment opportunity for GIP  and make GIP and CPP 2 
Investments the right partners for ALLETE.”9   3 
 4 
Q HOW WILL THE TRANSACTION AFFECT ALLETE’S CORPORATE 5 
STRUCTURE?  6 
A The Acquisition would dramatically change ALLETE’s governing structure post - 7 
closing.10 8 
 
IV.  ISSUES FOR HEARING AND BURDEN OF PROOF  9 
Q WHAT ARE THE ISSUES IN THIS PROCEEDING?  10 
A In its Order for Hearing, the Commission directed record development on a range of 11 
issues under a broad cost -benefit structure.  Specifically, the Commission directed 12 
record development on the following issues: 13 
A. Are there any potential harms to the public interest from the 14 
proposed transaction, including in relation to cost or risk?  15 
B. Are there any potential benefits to ratepayers, Minnesota, or the 16 
public interest from the proposed transaction?  17 
C. Considering all relevant factors and applicable law, is the 18 
proposed transaction consistent with the public interest?  19 
D. Are there regulatory requirements or commitments necessary to 20 
render the proposed transaction consistent with the public interest?  21 
E. How do relevant and related dockets pending before the Federal 22 
Energy Regulatory Commission, Public Service Commission of 23 
Wisconsin, and/or other state, federal or foreign government agencies 24 
impact the Commission’s consideration of the proposed transaction?  25 
F. How will the acquisition impact Minnesota Power’s union and 26 
non-union workforce and do the protections included in the acquisition 27 
adequately protect that workforce?  28 
 
9 Bram Direct  at 4 (emphasis added) ; see also  LPI IR 79, attached hereto as LPI Exhibit ___(CCW), 
Direct Schedule 2. 
10 See OAG IR 10 and 10.01 Attach, attached hereto as LPI Exhibit ___(CCW), Direct Schedule 2.  
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 6 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. G. How will the acquisition impact Minnesota Power's ability to 1 
comply with the carbon- free standard under Minn. Stat. § 216B.1691, 2 
including any modifications of plans associated with the Nemadji Trail 3 
Energy Center?11 4 
 
Q WHAT IS YOUR OVERALL ASSESSMENT OF THE APPLICANTS' 5 
TESTIMONY AND THEIR CASE IN SUPPORT OF THE PROPOSED 6 
ACQUISITION OF ALLETE?  7 
A The Applicants brought this proceeding seeking approval of the Acquisition.  As such, 8 
the Applicants bear the burden to demonstrate, under the issues outlined above by the 9 
Commission, that the Acquisition is consistent with the public interest.  Unfortunately, 10 
I have been unable to ascertain any evidence of meaningful benefit to the Company’s 11 
ratepayers or the public.  Therefore, I cannot conclude that the Applicants have met their 12 
burden of proof to demonstrate that the proposed A cquisition is consistent with the 13 
public interest.   Furthermore, it is unclear what benefits the Partners or ALLETE could 14 
offer to render the Acquisition consistent with the public interest.  15 
 Q IS THE BURDEN OF PROOF A SETTLED ISSUE IN THIS PROCEEDING?  16 
A No.  The Applicants acknowledge that “the definition of public interest…is derived 17 
from the vast body of energy policy developed over many years in Minnesota and for 18 
each new matter before the Commission will depend on the then- applicable statutes and 19 
rules and the circumstances of that matter. ”
12  I would characterize the burden of proof, 20 
and its application, as open issues for the Commission’s ultimate determination.  21 
 
11 Order for Hearing  at 12.  
12 CUB IR 37 , attached hereto as LPI Exhibit ___(CCW), Direct Schedule 2. 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 7 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC.  
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE YOUR CONCERNS.  1 
A Applicants claim that their commitments and proposed safeguards will protect 2 
Minnesota Power’s customers.  But their case is undermined by a consistent lack of 3 
transparency.  Throughout this proceeding, the Applicants have objected to many 4 
information requests, provided answers that were nonresponsive to intervenor and party 5 
inquiries, have provided heavily redacted responses to dozens of discovery requests, 6 
and have employed multiple levels of confidentiality designations, which only a very 7 
limited number of stakeholders were allowed to review, prevent ing meaningful review 8 
by intervenors.13 The Applicant’s  pattern of withholding critical information raises 9 
serious concerns about the veracity of their claims promising transparency  in future 10 
operations, assuming Acquisition approval .  11 
  In addition, the information that has been produced reveals staggering levels of 12 
investment, unsustainably large rate increases in the near term, and a general loss of  13 
control over  investment decisions.  These potential harms far outweigh any potential 14 
benefits, rendering the proposed Transaction in consistent with the public interest.  T he 15 
Commission should therefore reject the proposed T ransaction as the Applicants have 16 
failed to meet their burden of proof.  17 
   
 
13 See e.g, DOC IR 3  (objecting to use of a privilege log ) and CUB IR 53  (objecting to the “argumentative 
tone” of CUB IRs 1 -72); CUB IR 128 -129, objecting to the faulty premises of the question and referring to 
testimony instead of responding; CUB 158 (refusing to answer question in its entirety ), attached hereto as LPI 
Exhibit ___(CCW), Direct Schedule 2. 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]
Walters Direct  
Page 8 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. V.  POTENTIAL HARMS  1 
Q PLEASE SUMMARIZE THIS SECTION OF YOUR TESTIMONY . 2 
A In this section, I provide several examples of potential harms that could be attributed to 3 
the proposed Transaction, should it be completed.  Several potential harms are as 4 
follows:  5 
• The effect on customer rates is extraordinary.  The contemplated capital 6 
program risks infusing too much capital to grow rate base and earnings at an 7 
unsustainable pace, leading to unaffordable, unjust, and unreasonable rates.  8 
• [HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET INFORMATION 9 
BEGINS  …    
  
  
  
  
  
 … HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET 16 
INFORMATION ENDS] . 17 
• The dilution of Minnesota Power as a core division of ALLETE is 18 
concerning.  Minnesota Power is a foundational division of ALLETE , and 19 
ALLETE’s regulated operations represent approximately 8 9% of the 20 
projected capital expenditure plan  for the 2023- 2042 timeframe ,14 with 21 
 
14 See LPI IR 7, attached hereto as LPI Exhibit ___(CCW), Direct Schedule 2. 
[PUBLIC DOCUMENT – 
HIGHLY CONFIDENTIAL TRADE SECRET DATA EXCISED]

Walters Direct  
Page 9 
 
 
BRUBAKER & ASSOCIATES , INC. Minnesota Power alone comprising 87% of the projected capital plan.15  In 1 
comparison, if the Acquisition is approved, Minnesota Power will comprise 2 
a miniscule portion of the Partners ’ extensive holdings in other projects and 3

 Information Request No. 57 
Re:  Quackenbush Direct Testimony, Section III.B, p. 9:   “Investors require a return 
proportional to the risk of their investment.”  
Provide an analysis of how the transition from a publicly traded utility to private equity 
ownership will affect equity investors' required returns.  Include supporting evidence that private 
equity ownership will not result in an increased equity risk premium or higher required returns that 
might elevate the cost of capital for Minnesota Power.  
 
 RESPONSE : 
 The referenced quote is a statement of a general financial principle, not a reference to specific 
data.  Required returns are based on the risk of the investment, which does not change because of 
a transition from public to private market investors.  The cost of equity of an investment is 
related to the risk attributes of the investment, not to who happens to be the owner. Thus, the cost of equity for Minnesota Power can be estimated using methods similar to those utilized in the 
past in Minnesota rate proceedings . Please also see the response to CUB IR 0154 .

Information Request No. 67 
Re: Cady Direct, Section V, p. 18, footnote 5.  
Please confirm that slide #11 from the presentation referenced in footnote 5 demonstrates 
that Minnesota Power’s industrial electric rates have increased by roughly 127% as compared to 
the national average increase for industrial rates of roughly 53%, using 2005 as a starting point. 
Please explain how this increase is indicative of progress towards state energy policy set forth in 
Minn. Stat. § 216C.05, subd. 2(4).  
 RESPONSE : 
 The presentation referenced speaks for itself.  One factor affecting Minnesota Power’s rates since 2005 is the Company’s significant decarbonization of its energy supply.  In 2005, Minnesota Power’s energy supply had one of the highest carbon intensities in the nation, and by 2020 the 
Company delivered 50 percent renewable energy to customers.  Even with this significant 
transformation since 2005, Minnesota Power’s industrial rates exceeded 95 percent of the national average only beginning in 2020, and the national average has similarly increased since 
then.  Please see also Minnesota Power’s response to LPI IR 0065 discussing the Company’s 
continuing efforts toward competitive rates.

 Request:  
Reference Quackenbush Direct at  15:4-12: You refer here to the difference between an “occasional 
issuer ” and a “ serial issuer. ”  
(a) Define each term.  
(b) You say that ALLETE  is a serial issuer.  Is it a serial issuer because of its 40% role as a merchant 
seller, its 60% role as a state -franchised monopoly utility, or because of the combination of 
the two? Explain your answer.  
(c) Which of the two types would be Minnesota Power  be if it were a pure -play utility rather than 
a 60% division of ALLETE ?  
 
Response:  
(a) Occasional issuer means an issuer that issues infrequently, perhaps every 3 -5 years or even 
less often.  Serial issuer means an issuer with perpetually repeating issuance needs, 
perhaps with a need to issue every year or even more often.  
 
(b) ALLETE is a serial issuer because of its disproportionate outsized capital expenditure needs as identified in its five -year capital plan as well as its 20 -year Sustainability -in-Action 
strategy.  The capital plan is driven by a combination of all ALLETE’s divisions and subsidiaries.  However, as noted on page 16, lines 23 -24 of my Direct Testimony, 87% of 
ALLETE’s five -year capital plan is driven by Minnesota Power.  
 
(c) Minnesota Power’s capital needs would be the same whether it is structured as a division of ALLETE or a pure -play utility, so Minnesota Power would be a serial issuer either way.

 Response:  
 
The references in this IR draw two different partial sentences from two different prior IR 
responses  (DOC IR 0015 and DOC IR 0018), without the different questions asked in each IR 
or the full context provided in each IR response . The responses provided below should be read 
in the context of the complete responses provided for DOC IRs 0015 and/or 0018, as 
applicable.  
 
A. This was a reference to the process of requesting and receiving an equity infusion to fund capital requirements in a timely and efficient manner.  
 
B. Similar to the current process, ALLETE management will submit a capital budget and financing plan (for approval of both debt and equity issuance) to the board of directors. Once approved, an equity infusion will be provided by the Partners, while debt will  
continue to be issued by ALLETE.  As such, this process does not require a public equity 
issuance in order to obtain capital.  
 
C. As is their current practice, individual investment decisions by the Partners will continue 
to be made based on an assessment of the risk of the given investment and the expectation 
of the return required for and available from that investment. The Partners decided to 
pursue the Acquisition and invest in ALLETE knowing the anticipated future capital requirements of Minnesota Power to meet Minnesota’s Carbon Free Standard and ALLETE’s capital plan , and the Partners support ALLETE’s desire to achieve its goals. 
Please see the response to DOC IR 0007 for an explanation regarding how the Partners 
each build and allocate capital.   
D. See OAG IR 0 005(C) above . 
 
E. ALLETE will not be exposed to public equity investors.  However, ALLETE will continue to secure its own debt financing, so it will still have exposure to debt investors who must decide if they are willing to commit capital to the Company with reasonable risk adjusted 
returns.  
 
F. GIP Fund V is a private investment limited partnership.  The fund will be insulated from public markets in that it has already raised sufficient funds to support the current and future 
investments in ALLETE. Additionally, the fund has a long -term investment horizon that is 
focused on earning reasonable returns over time and is able to exercise patience with 
respect to quarterly earnings and dividends. For additional information, see the Direct Testimony of GIP W itness Bram.

Subparts (A) and (B) of this IR draw two different partial sentences from two different prior IR 
responses (CUB IR 0043 and DOC IR 0019), without the different questions asked in each IR or the full context provided in each IR response.    The responses provided below should be read in 
the context of the complete responses provided for CUB IR 0043 and/or DOC IR 0019, as applicable.   
A. The Acquisition would allow ALLETE access to equity capital without the added costs that would be expected in the future if ALLETE needed to finance its capital plan in 
public markets. Eventually this will reduce or remove the need for additional flotation 
costs to be incurred on future issuances, which would be factored into future cost recovery proceedings.   (This does not reduce or remove prior flotation costs incurred.) 
While the Company cannot speculate about actual future savings amounts, please see subpart (C).

secondary offerings, which would add significant incremental costs and risks in access 
equity capital in the future. The Company cannot speculate about actual future incremental cost amounts.   
C. Throughout ALLETE’s history, secondary equity offerings have included flotation costs that have generally ranged between 3 -4 percent of the gross equity offering amount, in 
addition to the offering discount necessary to attract potential investors. Given the need for 
approximately $1 billion in external equity in the next fi ve years alone, as discussed in the 
Direct Testimony of Company Witness  Taran, this would add significant costs to 
Minnesota Power’s cost of capital in the future. Additionally, as discussed in the Direct 
Testimony of Company Witness Scissons, the need to raise this level of capital would 
require a large expansion of ALLETE’s investor base, which would require additional investor relations expenses and staff, though specific amounts of added costs have not been 
quantified at this time.  
 
D. See CUB IR 0077, access to which will be provided upon appropriate completion of Non -
Disclosure Agreements.  
E. No, the Partners will not assess flotation costs for equity capital infusions to ALLETE or 
Minnesota Power.

Topic:   Access to capital  
 
Reference:  
 
• CUB IR 83(a).  Response states that CUB is incorrect in suggesting that “Minnesota 
Power’s access to capital for unspecified ‘future needs’ would be insufficient without the Acquisition.”  
 
Request:    
 
Is the response to CUB IR 83 saying that Minnesota Power’s access to capital would be sufficient 
without the proposed acquisition?  Explain.  
 Response:  
 No. While ALLETE has been able to navigate the risks of public markets to date , the outsized and 
ongoing nature of the projected capital needs presents a significant risk.  As stated in the Direct 
Testimony of Company witness  Taran  (Section III.A.) , the Company’s operations alone will not 
generate sufficient cash flow to fund the significant capital expenditure projections . As a result , 
the Company would not be able to make the necessary investments to meet the state’s clean energy standard without external capital. Without the Acquisition, Minnesota Power may  be forced to 
delay investments that are necessary to continue providing safe, reliable service to customers, at 
likely  higher costs. Even if ALLETE were able to access the public markets at the scale  necessary , 
the risk and cost of such access for a Company of ALLETE’s size is difficult to predict and unlikely 
to be reliable, given the unique customer concentration profile for Minnesota Power and the 
volatility in the  public stock market.

development assets. GIP is well positioned to support and reduce the risks of Minnesota 22 
Power’s growth plan in the long -term. This will allow Minnesota Power to maintain strong 23 
operational performance, execute its mission of decarbonization, and increase its value, 24 
which will benefit GIP’s investors, Minnesota Power’s customers, and other stakeholders. 25 
26 
Q. Please briefly describe the partner  entities that will become owners of ALLETE. 27 
A. Upon closing of the Acquisition, a wholly  owned subsidiary of CPP Investments will 28 
acquire 40  percent of the outstanding common stock of ALLETE. GIP will hold the 29 
remaining 60 percent of the interests in ALLETE through two funds: Global Infrastructure 30

14 Q. In addition to utilities, does GIP own and operate other regulated infrastructure 1 
assets?  2 
A. Yes, GIP has been managing and investing in other regulated assets (e.g. airports, ports, 3 
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission -regulated midstream assets) since investing 4 
through its first Flagship Fund, GIP Fund I, in 2009 . A good example of GIP’s regulated 5 
infrastructure investments is its investment in Gatwick Airport (“Gatwick”).  Gatwick is the 6 
second largest airport in the United Kingdom  and is regulated by the Civil Aviation 7 
Authority (the United Kingdom’s aviation regulator). GIP initially invested in Gatwick 8 
through GIP Fund I in December 2009  and continues to invest in Gatwick today . During 9 
this time , Gatwick has modernized and expanded the airport facilities, improved the 10 
passenger experience , and ranked as the world’s most efficient and busiest single runway 11 
airport.   12 
 13 
Q. Please describe GIP’s prior investments and experience in the renewable energy 14 
sector.  15 
A. GIP is a leading investor in the renewables sector across key geographies and technologies 16 
and has significant experience scaling and de -risking platforms. Approximately a quarter 17 
of GIP’s investments to date have involved renewables. GIP’s renewable portfolio is one 18 
of the largest renewables platforms in the United States  and globally. GIP’s current 19 
renewables portfolio includes approximately $15 billion of equity invested or committed 20 
across 22 GW in operation, or in 23 GW of operating or under -construction renewables 21 
projects royalty interests, and approximately 176 GW under construction or in 22 
development. GIP has invested in large -scale renewables businesses in the United States , 23 
Latin America, Europe, and Asia -Pacific through its ownership of Vena Energy, Clearway 24 
Energy, Eolian, Chile Renovables, Bluepoint Wind (formerly referred to as NY Bight), 25 
Skyborn Renewables (formerly wpd Offshore), Atlas Renewables, and its joint ventures 26 
with Ørsted.  27

15 Q. Does GIP have a specific focus when looking at potential  investments ?  1 
A. GIP pursues a differentiated investment strategy and specific assessment process. Part of 2 
GIP’s investment assessment process involves a rigorous and independent risk and ESG 3 
assessment, including a focus on carbon reduction (decarbonization) throughout the life 4 
cycle of an investment . The acceleration of climate action, decarbonization , and energy 5 
transition are at the core of GIP’s approach to investing and operating our businesses  and 6 
represent a strategic opportunity and potential value driver for our target sectors and 7 
portfolio companies.  GIP focuses on investments in these areas because GIP has 8 
determined that they present opportunities to deploy large amounts of capital that will result 9 
in long -term, stable returns for investors.  GIP expects all traditional infrastructure sectors 10 
to face a similar need for significant capital investment and has therefore developed a 11 
focused and careful approach to new infrastructure investments. 12 
13 
Q. How does that specific focus relate to the Company ? 14 
A. GIP’s investment in the Company  is an excellent example of what this assessment process 15 
and investment strategy look like in practice. As I explained above, GIP’s decision to 16 
pursue the Acquisition is directly tied to Minnesota Power’s  plan to decarbonize its 17 
generation fleet while investing concurrently in its transmission and distribution systems 18 
in order to deliver this decarbonized power to its customers and comply with Minnesota’s 19 
Carbon Free Standard  policy.  ALLETE already has attractive renewables platforms across 20 
utility -scale wind and distributed solar generation and the Partners are committed to 21 
supporting and helping grow these platforms. More generally , the Company  also has a 22 
robust ESG organization with well-established policies, reporting, and governance 23 
practices committed to addressing climate risk and focused on positive stakeholder impacts 24 
including commitments to invest in its communities, economic development, and to protect 25 
low-income customers. 26

Scissons  Direct  Q. How does Minnesota Power currently undertake the development of strategy and 1 
planning? 2 
A. Minnesota Power’s strategy development is a comprehensive and collaborative process 3 
that is led by a dedicated cross -functional team of experts. The team aggregates and 4 
considers key inputs from both within the Company and from external sources including 5 
customer data and forecasts, technology assessments, policy and regulatory guidelines, 6 
energy markets, operational realities and stakeholder input to develop Integrated 7 
Resource Plan s (“IRP”) and Integrated Distribution Plan s (“IDP”) that guide  Minnesota 8 
Power’s  future investments upon Commission approval. 9 
10 
Q. Are changes to strategy and planning for Minnesota Power anticipated after the 11 
Acquisition? 12 
A. No changes as to how Minnesota Power develops its strategy are anticipated after the 13 
Acquisition. Currently, talented professionals at Minnesota Power develop strategic 14 
plans and submit them to the Board for approval. Following the transaction , strategic 15 
plans will still be developed by professionals at Minnesota Power and submitted to the 16 
Board for approval , and the strategic planning is expected to be developed by the same 17 
teams and individuals because of commitments by the Partners to the continuity of 18 
Minnesota Power’s workforce . Additionally, as further detailed in the Direct Testimony 19 
of Company Witness Cady, the Partners are supportive of Minnesota Power’s 20 
collaborative approach to stakeholder engagement going forward. 21 
22 
While the Partners have extensive experience with infrastructure assets, t hey do not 23 
have or intend to hire personnel that could replace the Company’s current teams or 24 
expertise. Through diligence of the existing Minnesota Power strategy, the Partners are 25 
aligned and committed to support the execution of the ALLETE strategy with the 26 
existing team. In short, t he Partners ’ role post -Acquisition would be similar to that of 27 
the current ALLETE Board.  28
